7 contribute to long-term rate stability.
8 (iv) Reliability. In evaluating reliability, the commission
9 shall consider operational availability, dispatchability, fuel
10 security, and performance under a range of operating conditions. As
11 used in this subparagraph, "reliability" means the capacity of a
12 generation resource or portfolio to deliver uninterrupted
13 electricity to meet system demand, including during peak usage,
14 severe weather, or system stress.
15 (v) Commodity price risks. In evaluating commodity price
16 risks, the commission shall prioritize long-term rate stability for
17 customers. The commission shall conduct a sensitivity analysis that
18 complies with both of the following:
19 (A) Except as provided in sub-subparagraph (B), the commission
20 shall apply a risk premium to any generation resource dependent on
21 a fuel source that has demonstrated historical price volatility
22 exceeding 15% over any 5-year period in the preceding 20 years.
23 (B) The commission shall waive the volatility risk premium
24 required under sub-subparagraph (A) for a resource if both of the
25 following occur:
26 (I) The electric utility secures a long-term firm fuel
27 transportation contract or fixed-price fuel hedging instrument for
28 the resource for a period of not less than 5 years, the resource is
29 capable of maintaining a minimum of 18 months of on-site fuel
KHS H02431'25 a (H-1) 8jyogi

40
1 supply, or, for a natural gas resource, the electric utility has
2 access to firm underground storage capacity sufficient to maintain
3 continuous full-load output for a period of not less than 30 days.
4 (II) The commission determines that the projected total cost
5 of the firm fuel contract, hedging instrument, or storage agreement
6 is lower than the sum of the projected market cost of equivalent
7 spot market procurement and the volatility risk premium required
8 under sub-subparagraph (A).
9 (vi) Diversity of generation supply. In evaluating diversity of
10 generation supply, the commission shall consider whether the
11 proposed resource portfolio enhances overall system reliability,
12 affordability, and fuel security. The commission shall not favor or
13 disfavor any particular energy resource or technology solely on the
14 basis of environmental attributes or policy goals not established
15 by statute. A resource shall not be excluded from consideration for
16 purposes of diversity if it is cost-effective, dispatchable, or
17 contributes to grid stability. As used in this subparagraph,
18 "diversity of generation supply" means the inclusion of a balanced
19 mix of electricity generation resources utilizing different fuel
20 types, technologies, and operational characteristics for the
21 purpose of reducing reliance on any single energy source or supply
22 chain.
23 (vii) Whether the proposed levels of peak load reduction and
24 energy waste reduction are reasonable and cost-effective. In
25 evaluating whether the proposed levels of peak load reduction are
26 reasonable and cost-effective, the commission shall consider the
27 expected impact of those measures on system capacity needs,
28 resource adequacy, and overall electric system performance, the
29 total cost of implementing the measures compared to the avoided
KHS H02431'25 a (H-1) 8jyogi

41
1 costs of energy and capacity, and the effect of the measures on
2 customer bills and rate stability. As used in this subparagraph,
3 "cost-effective" means that the projected benefits of the proposed
4 measures exceed their total costs over the expected duration of the
5 program, and that the measures can be implemented in a manner that
6 does not compromise electric system reliability or materially
7 increase costs to ratepayers.
8 (viii) Affordability. In evaluating affordability, the
9 commission shall consider capital, fuel, operation and maintenance,
10 and decommissioning costs, levelized cost of energy or capacity,
11 projected impacts on customer bills and overall rate stability, and
12 long-term cost escalations, contingencies, and revenue
13 requirements. As used in this subparagraph, "affordability" means
14 the capacity of a generation resource or portfolio to deliver
15 electricity at a cost that minimizes the total financial burden on
16 ratepayers over the resource's expected operational life.
17 (ix) Overall cost-effectiveness in providing utility service.
18 (b) To the extent practicable, the construction or investment
19 in a new or existing capacity resource in this state is completed
20 using a workforce composed of residents of this state as determined
21 by the commission. This subdivision does not apply to a capacity
22 resource that is located in a county that lies on the border with
23 another state.
24 (c) The construction and construction maintenance of new or
25 the rehabilitation of existing capacity resources in this state
26 includes using an apprenticeship program registered and certified
27 with the United States Secretary of Labor under the national
28 apprenticeship act, 29 USC 50 to 50c, and the workers employed for
29 the construction or construction maintenance of the energy facility
KHS H02431'25 a (H-1) 8jyogi

42
1 are paid a minimum wage standard not less than the wage and fringe
2 benefit rates prevailing in the locality in which the work is to be
3 performed as determined under 2023 PA 10, MCL 408.1101 to 408.1126,
4 or 40 USC 3141 to 3148, whichever provides the higher wage and
5 fringe benefit rates, and, to the extent permitted by law, the
6 entities performing the construction or construction maintenance
7 work shall enter into a project labor agreement or operate under a
8 collective bargaining agreement for the work to be performed. This
9 subdivision does not apply to an independent power producer
10 supplying power under a contract or agreement entered into in
11 accordance with the public utility regulatory policies act of 1978,
12 Public Law 95-617, as of the effective date of the amendatory act
13 that added this subdivision. As used in this subdivision, "project
14 labor agreement" means a prehire collective bargaining agreement
15 with 1 or more labor organizations that establishes the terms and
16 conditions of employment for a specific construction project and
17 does all of the following:
18 (i) Binds all contractors and subcontractors on the
