48
1 exceed the costs approved by the commission, the electric utility
2 has the burden of proving by a preponderance of the evidence that
3 the costs are reasonable and prudent. The portion of the cost of a
4 plant, facility, power purchase agreement, or other investment in a
5 resource that meets a demonstrated need for capacity that exceeds
6 the cost approved by the commission is presumed to have been
7 incurred due to a lack of prudence. The commission may include any
8 or all of the portion of the cost in excess of the cost approved by
9 the commission if the commission finds by a preponderance of the
10 evidence that the costs are reasonable and prudent. The commission
11 shall disallow costs the commission finds have been incurred as the
12 result of fraud, concealment, gross mismanagement, or lack of
13 quality controls amounting to gross mismanagement. The commission
14 shall also require refunds with interest to ratepayers of any of
15 these costs already recovered through the electric utility's rates
16 and charges. If the assumptions underlying an approved integrated
17 resource plan materially change, or if the commission believes it
18 is unlikely that a project or program will become commercially
